Moral dilemmas for Fannie and Freddie
NEW HAVEN: The takeover of the mortgage giants Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac by the U.S. government represents an enormous bailout for the creditors of these institutions, whose losses have continued to grow as housing prices fell.
Now that the government is fully on the hook for Fannie and Freddie's debts, American taxpayers will have to pay for everything that was not covered by the insufficient financial resources of their creditors.
Why such a rescue operation in what is arguably the most openly capitalist country in the world?
Do not the time-honored principles of capitalism include the idea that those who believed in the real estate bubble and invested their money in Fannie and Freddie should now bear the losses?
Is it fair that innocent taxpayers now have to pay for their mistakes?
The answers to these questions would be obvious if the moral issues of the current financial crisis were clearly defined.
But they are not.
Primarily, it is unclear whether the bailout will actually cost U.S. taxpayers anything in the end. Maybe it prevents further systemic effects that could bring down the financial sector and thus the world economy.
Just because systemic effects are difficult to quantify does not mean they do not exist.
Furthermore, the securities issued by Fannie and Freddie were widely regarded as being backed by an implicit guarantee of the US government.
Although there was no official guarantee, the absence of a rescue action by the US government could undermine confidence in government securities and, because they are associated with these, also in other financial instruments.
The problems extend far beyond the US economy.
The world economy has been driven in recent years by remarkable speculative highs and lows in asset values, raising questions of trust but also fairness in the equation.
Similar booms in the housing sectors are currently coming to an end in many other countries, and they may face the same challenges – and the same moral dilemmas – that the US economy is currently experiencing.
And the problem is not just the housing markets.
The stock markets are also affected.
The Chinese Shanghai Composite Index rose by a factor of 5 between 2005 and 2007 and then lost two-thirds of its real value.
The Sensex in India rose by a factor of 5 in real terms between 2003 and 2007 and has since lost one-third of its value.
Similar stock market highs and crashes have occurred in many other countries as well.
As long as they continued, the preceding boom phases led to overheating of these economies.
Now that they have reversed, a loss of confidence could grip the world economy and push it into recession.
To prevent this, some selected bailouts may be necessary – not to support the market, but to address injustices.
There is no precise science of trust; there is no way to predict how people will react when help is absent as markets collapse.
People's reactions to such events depend on their feelings and sense of justice.
The described highs and lows have caused a major redistribution of wealth.
Those who invested on the stock market or real estate market fared well or poorly depending on when they timed their investments.
People will judge the fairness of these results based on what was told to them and the implicit promises they derived from it.
What was told to people in all these countries about the markets they invested their money in?
Was everything really true?
Unfortunately, there is no way to find out.
Policy can only react generally and not deal with each case individually.
We know that recent economic growth in many countries was spectacular.
But were the investments in their markets overpriced?
Have cynical sellers here and elsewhere led people to believe that boom times would bring prosperity for everyone?
Surely, although there has been a lot of "cheap talk" – general advice with reservations – many of the losers in this game are not hungry.
But we cannot conclude from this that we should let them bear all their losses without concern.
The persistent problem is one of "trust and confidence".
National economies flourish only when "trust and confidence" prevail.
The current situation, where speculative booms have driven the world economy – and now, after their collapse, are pushing it into recession – suggests that people who promoted certain investments did so against the principles of trust and confidence.
Take the investors who bought Fannie and Freddie securities.
Although the US government never officially promised to come to their aid, it established a special agency, the Office of Federal Housing Enterprise Oversight, whose task was to assess their strength in an annual report.
But this agency never even acknowledged that there was a housing bubble.
Top government officials never issued any warnings.
Can we therefore really claim that investors must bear all the consequences of their losses?
How could this be fair?
The world is discovering the power and transformation of capitalism on national economies.
But capitalism relies on trust and integrity.
An unfair treatment can be lethal for economic growth, as it means people will lose their trust in companies and thus be less willing to provide them with valuable capital and labor.
Is such a result preferable to a bailout from a moral standpoint?
